To clarify. The loan duration matches first charge. Eg can be up to 40 years. You can repay it at any point or keep it for full length, it's just that you have a 5 year fixed interest period.
Yep. That’ll, er, work. Not
Thanks for the info.
It's an equity loan. If prices fall, we share the loss. If prices go up, we share the gains (but only 15%, rest goes to home buyer).
And if prices fall? Just original loan amount repayable or indexed against something else?
Yes. Repayable after 5 years. For 5% deposit buyers, it ends up reducing monthly payments approx 20%, increasing affordability by around 15%, allowing them to own their home up to 10 years earlier.
